{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_jarlsburg_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868909/1930112101/0675.xml":{"full_text":"The reconstruction of society\non a scientific basis is not only\npossible, but it is the only politi\ncal object worth working for.\nCharles Kingsley.\nVol. 19\u2014No. 296.\nHUNDREDS ARE TRAPPED IN DLIZZARD\nLegge States Federal\nEnforcers Gave 0 K on\n\u201cMagic Keg\u201d Juices\nWASHINGTON The federal\nfarm board had assurances from the\nprohibition enforcement agencies\nthat the grape wine concentrate\nfrom \u201cmagic kegs\u201d was \u201cperfectly\nlegal,\u201d Chairman Alexander Legge\nof the farm board declared yester\nday in explaining the financial back\ning given the California grape con\ntrol board.\nLegge\u2019s First Statement.\nIt was Legge\u2019s first lengthy dis\ncussion of the grape juice sales\nwhich has caused nation-wide inter\nest following a federal raid on a\nSt. Louis store in which the juice\nwas sold to agents and they in turn\nwere told how to process the juice\nfor wine.\nProhibition Director Amos W. W.\nWoodcock said the raiders were\nwithin their rights as \u201cintent\u201d had\nbeen clearly shown.\nGiven Official 0 K.\n\u201cThe farm board has a clear file\non the sales campaign of the grape\nindustry,\u201d Legge said. \u201cI corre\nsponded with everybody in the gov\nernment about it. I told them we\ndid not want to lend money for\nany enterprise that would be illegal,\nTurn to Page Two. Column Eight.\nU. S. LAUNCHES\nDRIVE TO WIPE\nOUT GANGLAND\nBY CECIL OWEN.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe United Press\nWASHINGTON\u2014Organized rack\neteering faced an organized govern\nment campaign today, with the fed\neral offensive pl 'dged to continue\nuntil gangland has been whipped\ninto submission.\nOutlining the most extensive fed\neral effort ever undertaken against\nlocal crime. Attorney General Mit\nchell told of a co-ordinated drive by\nall government law enforcement\nagencies against gangsters.\nStarted Last Summer.\nThe campaign was instituted\nearly last summer when the Hoover\nadministration realized that the un\nchecked growth of racketeering in\nChicago and elsewhere constituted\na threat to law and order on a na\ntional scale.\nBecause the situation is more\nacute in Chicago than elsewhere,\nMitchell said a special agent was\nsent there from Washington to act\nas assistant to the United States dis\ntrict attorney and to coordinate the\nwork of all government agencies.\nWould Exterminate Gangs.\nThe government branches con\ncerned in the war include the justice\ndepartment, prohibition bureau, nar\ncotics bureau, immigration service,\nsecret service, industrial alcohol\nbureau, coast guard and customs\nservice.\nExtermination of gangland is the\nobject of the current drive and Mit\nchell said it will be continued in\ndefinitely until effective results are\nobtained.\nFederal laws are being invoked\nwhereever necessary to aid local\nofficials who are unable for various\nreasons to obtain convictions in\ntheir own courts. The federal law\nmost commonly used is the income\ntax law which carries heavy penal\nties for failure to report all income.\nThe Washington Post is undoubtedly one of the most\nconservative \u2014not to say reactionary\u2014newspapers in the\nUnited States.\nAnd yet, in its issue of last Sunday, it printed a most\nenlightened editorial on the fundamental causes of the\npresent depression. The editorial is so admirable in\nform and substance that The Milwaukee Leader prints\nit in full as follows:\n\u201cCAUSE OF THE CRASH.\n\u201cOut of many diagnoses of the business depression\neconomists have arrived at the conclusion that the coun\ntry produced in the years immediately preceding the\ncrash more goods than the public could consume with its\nlimited buying power. The resultant surplus became a\ndrug on the market, and it was necessary to curtail pro\nduction while the slack was being taken up.\n\u201cUntil now this has been mere theory. But figures\nthat have just been worked out by the census bureau\nsustain the theory beyond doubt. The fact that there was\nan \u2018overproduction\u2019 can no longer be questioned.\n\u201cBut why did a surplus of goods bring hard times\nwhen thousands of people are in need of more clothes,\nbetter food, and more substantial houses, as well as the\nconveniences and luxuries of life?\n\u201cThe reason reaches far back into history. In 1849,\naccording to figures of the census bureau, the manufac\nturing industries of the United States produced goods\nThe Milwaukee Leader\nPOST GUARDS\nAT HOME OF\nGRAPE CHIEF\nHILLSBORO, Calif.\u2014A police\nguard was maintained today at\nthe home of Doland D. Conn,\nmanager of Fruit Industries, Inc.,\nwhich manufactures a grape\njuice concentrate that turns into\nwine under proper conditions.\nReports that \u201cScarface Al\u201d Ca\npone, Chicago gang leader, in\ntends to prevent sale of the con\ncentrate in Chicago were believed\nresponsible for the guard. A\ndozen policemen were sent to\nguard Conn\u2019s home, reportedly on\nhis request.\nPolice also were tracing a long\ndistance telephone call from San\nMateo to Chicago that ran up a\ntoll of several hundred dollars.\nThey were told that two men\nasked for the connection and paid\nlater from a large roll of bills.\nGermany Will\nSeek Relief\nOn War Debt\nBERLIN Germany may be\nforced to invoke the safeguard\nmeasures of the Young plan, For\neign Minister Julius Curtius an\nnounced last night.\nThese safeguard measures refer\nto a moratorium and the convoca\ntion of a special advisory mmit\ntte to bring about alleviations per\nmissible under the plan. The for\neign minister\u2019s speech constituted\nGermany\u2019s first official intimation\nthat she is likely to invoke her\nright under the plan to declare a\nmoratorium.\nHerr Curtins chose an opportune\nmoment for his speech, after the\nreichsrat had passed virtually all\nlegislation connected with the gov\nernment\u2019s financial program. The\nreichsrat had unanimously ap\nproved the budget, and also a bill\nreducing the salaries of cabinet\nmembers, reichstag members and\ncivil service employes.\nAt the same time Herr Curtius ex\npressed sharp criticism of Europe\u2019s\nsluggish attitude toward disarma\nment and in connection with a re\ncent speech on that issue by pre\nmier Tardieu of France, he declared\nGermany would demand an early\ndisarmament conference, \u201cwhere\neach nation must show its colors\nand its real intentions.\u201d\nRumboat Captured\nAfter Bombardment\nNEW LONDON, Conn.\u2014Her pilot\nhouse shattered by gunfire, the 50-\nfoot speedboat Happy Parrot, carry\ning three men and a cargo of about\n400 cases of alleged liquor, was\nbrought to the coast guard base to\nday. An unnamed coast guard ves\nsel captured the Happy Parrot late\nlast night after an eight-mile chase\nfrom Block island to Fisher\u2019s\nisland, during which many shots\nwere fired from the patrol boat\u2019s\none-pound gun.\nBank Closing Total Swells to 89\nANOTHER FIRM\nASKS FOR AID\nBY EMPLOYES\nHelp for Those Laid\nOff Sought From\nWorkers.\nThe movement on foot among a\nnumber of large private corpora\ntions to get workers still lucky\nenough to have a job to contribute\npart of their pay to funds with\nwhich these companies announce\nthey will help those whom they\nhave laid off has gained another\nadherent. The Railway Express\nagency yesterday announced the in\nauguration of such a scheme,\nthrough its Chicago office.\nThe statement of the express com\npany announcing this plan like the\nstatements of the Milwaukee and\nthe Northwestern railroads, details\nof which yere previously reported\nin The Milwaukee Leader, says\nnothing about the company itself\ncontributing any money to the plan.\nSays Many Laid Off.\nIn connection with the announce\nment, E. A. Steadman, vice presi\ndent, stated that the business de\npression had made it necessary to\nreduce the working force of the\ncompany and that in many cases\nformer employes had been unable\nto secure other work.\n\u201cThe readiness with which large\ncorporations are inaugurating such\nschemes, show that there is a defi\nnite attempt being made to shift the\nresponsibility for taking care of\nthe unemployed from industry,\nwhich is responsible for unemploy\nment, to the workers,\u201d J. F. Frfed\nrick, a member of the Federated\nTrades council special unemploy\nment committee, said.\nRailway Boasts Empty.\n\u201cAt the annual meeting of the\nNational Association of Railroad\nExecutives, held in New York yes\nterday, a statement containing the\nfollowing was issued:\n\u2018Upon request of the president of\nthe United States, in the latter part\nof 1929, the railroads undertook an\nextensive program of construction\nand building of equipment in order\nto offset the threat of a substantial\nsuspension of business activity.\u2019\n\u201cOn the other hand the commerce\ncommission reports that during that\ntime when this extensive program\nof construction was supposed to\nhave been under way, between Sep\ntember, 1929, and September, 1930,\n262,000 fewer workers were em\nployed on the railroads.\u201d\nKilled on Farm\nBlasting Stumps\nBEAVER DAM, Wis. Donald\nRoberts, 25 years old, was instantly\nkilled and his uncle, Hugh Roberts,\n45 years old, was seriously injured\nnear here today when a charge of\ndynamite prematurely exploded.\nthe men had been blasting\nstumps on the Roberts homestead\nand Donald was leaning directly\nover the charge when it exploded.\nThe uncle was standing nearby.\nHe received burns about the face\nand body and may lose the sight of\none eye.\n\u201cHard Times\u201d\u2014The Cause and the Cure\nvalued at approximately $1,000,000,000 and paid $236,-\n755,000 in wages.\n\u201cSince that time both wages and the value of prod\nucts have increased enormously. In 1929 the output of\nthe manufacturing industries reached the highest point\nin history. Goods turned out by American plants were\nvalued at $68,000,000,000.\n\u201cHad industry paid the same proportion of this re\nturn in wages as it did in 1849, wage earners would have\nreceived an aggregate of $16,000,000,000. Instead, they\nwere paid $11,271,116,000.\n\u201cMany factors such as the cost of machinery and the\ngreater expenses of distribution enter into this compari\nson, but these figures are sufficient to contradict the\npopular belief that wages are high in America.\n\u201cOn the basis of productive capacity American labor\nis cheap.\n\u201cA study of the increases in both wages and industry\nsuggests that the working man is not yet receiving his\nfull share of the wealth he helps to create.\n\u201cA glance at the more recent figures is more con\nvincing. During 1927 wages amounted to $10,848,802,000\nand the products of the manufacturing industries were\nworth $62,718,347,000. Wages increased in the following\ntwo years by $422,214,000, in spite of, the fact that fewer\nworkmen were employed. But during that same period\nproduction was augmented to the extent of $5,735,139,000.\n\u201cIn other words* labor registered a gain of 3.8 per\nFRIDAY EVENING, NOVEMBER 21, 1930.\nJudge Holds\nYellow Dog\nPact Illegal\nPORTLAND, Ore. \u2014Circuit Judge\nWalter H. Evans has rendered an\nopinion holding the yellow dog con\ntract invalid. In the case of the\nIce Delivery Co. vs. Frank Irons,\nan injunction is denied the com\npany.\nThe Ice Delivery Co. is a merger\nof several ice companies. Irons had\nbeen employed as a delivery man\nfor several years in a certain dis\ntrict of the city.\nAfter the merger he was forced\nto sign a contract forfeiting his\nrights as to accepting employment\nfrom any competing firm and, with\nout naming the union, making pos\nsible his discharge if he did join a\nunion.\nLast May, Irons became a mem\nber of the Drivers\u2019 union and two\nTurn to Page Three, Column One.\nTWO SUSPECTS\nOF MURDER IN\nCHICAGO HELD\nChicago detectives are expected\nto come to Milwaukee today to\nquestion two brothers believed\nthose sought in investigation of the\nmurder of Jack Guida, Chicago\nracketeer, in a speakeasy there Oct.\n23.\nThe men, captured last night in\na rooming house at 103 East Mitch\nell st., by Milwaukee detectives or.\na tip from Chicago, identified them\nselves as William, 23 years old, and\nFrank Carr, 30 years old, alias\nWilliam and Frank Davis.\nA third man is still sought. He\nis believed to have been living with\nthe Carrs. Three automatic revol\nvers were found in their room.\nINDIA FEDERAL\nSTATE PLEDGED\nBY M\u2019DONALD\nLONDON\u2014An offer of a federal\nform for government for India was\ncontained in a speech by J. Ramsay\nMacDonald, Socialist and Labor\npremier, at the round table confer\nence on India today.\nMacDonald, concluding the sec\nond plenary session of the confer\nence, said the Indians were not in\na position to produce at once a per\nmanent constitution, but that one\nwill be evolved.\nThe British government will not\ngo back on any pledges it had made\ntoward .the achievement of a re\nsponsible Indian government, Mac-\nDonald promised.\nHe referred particularly to the\nBritish pledges prior to the Mon\ntague Chelmsford declaration of\n1917 pledging the development of\nself-governing institutions in India.\nFRESH WAVE\nHITS BANKS IN\nTHREE STATES\nSix Indiana Houses\nAct to Suspend\nOperations.\nWith the closing of 15 more\nbanks in Indiana. Tennessee and\nNorth Carolina today and late\nyesterday, the total number of\nbanks closings in the central and\nsouth central states since Mon\nday swelled to 89.\nINDIANA? OLIS, Ind. Six\nsouthern Indiana banks were closed\ntoday by voluntary action of their\ndirectors. Officials said the closing\nresulted from disturbed banking\nconitions in Louisville.\nThe closed institutions were the\nNew Albany Liberty State bank; the\nAmerican Bank and Trust Co. of\nNew Albany, the Crawford County\nState bank of English, the Leaven\nworth State bank of Leavenworth,\nthe Jackson Township State bank\nof Corydon Junction and the Old\nCapitol Bank and Trust Co. of Cory\ndon.\nTennessee Bank Shut.\nPARIS, Tenn.\u2014The First State\nBank and Trust Co. of Paris, with\ntotal resources of $1,000,000, failed\nto open today.\nNorth Carolina Hit.\nASHEVILLE, N. C The Amer\nican National bank of Asheville,\nwith deposits of nearly $2,000,000.\nand the Citizens\u2019 bank of Bryson\nCity, N. C., closed today, bringing\nto 10 the number of banks to halt\noperations in this state in two days.\nThe Central Bank\u2019and Trust Co.\nhere failed yesterday, censing four\nother banks to close and tying up\ndeposits of more than $22,000,000.\nClosing of two other small banks\nin this vicinity was announced later\nin the day, but it was said there\nwas no connection between their\nsituation and the Central Bank and\nTrust Co.\u2019s failure.\nThey were the Clay County bank\nof Hayesville with SIO,OOO capital\nand SIIO,OOO deposits, and the Bank\nof Leiscester, Buncombe county,\n$20,000 capital and $105,00 deposits.\nThe Bank of Lowell, at Lowell,\n12 miles east of Charlotte, also\nclosed yesterday.\nThe other banks closing were the\nBiltmore-Oteen bank in Biltmore,\nAsheville suburb, with a capital of\n$50,000 and deposits of $615.051;\nthe First Bank and Trust Co., Hen\ndersonville. capital $150,000 and de\nposits of $1,207,628; the Citizens\nNational bank, Hendersonville, capi\ntal $100,000; deposits, $1,077,397,\n\u2019and the American Bank and Trust\nCo.. Hendersonville, capital $50,000,\ndeposits $111,638.\nMILL AT OCONTO\nWILL HIRE 300\nOCONTO, Wis.\u2014The Holt Lum\nber Co. sawmill will open Nov. 24\nto run steadily throughout the win\nter, according to an announcement\nhere today by President W. A. Holt.\nSeveral hundred families will be\ncertain of an income during the cold\nmonths as a result of the opening.\ncent in its purchasing power, while the output of indus\ntry gained more than 9 per cent.\n\u201cIn these figures lies the story of the industrial de\npression. While goods were being turned out at a pace\nnever before equaled in history, the buying power of the\npublic was making but small gains.\n\u201cWhen the climax was reached in the last months\nof 1929 a period of adversity was inevitable because the\npeople did not have sufficient money to buy the surplus\ngoods which they had produced.\n\u201cThis diagnosis having been supported by inescap\nable facts, the remedy becomes a matter of applying the\neconomic law which those facts suggest. If the country\nis to go on producing at the 1929 level, the buying power\nof the people must be increased.\n\u201cConsuming power already exists, and it has no\nlimitations. From the long-range view, all that is neces\nsary to make it effective is to increase the earning power\nof the workman\u2019s family.\n\u201cIt is estimated that at least 85 per cent of all goods\nproduced in America must be consumed by those families\nactually engaged in the task of production, if a surplus\nis to be avoided. Mass production on any other basis\nis impossible.\n\u201cWhen the industrial processes are speeded up by\nthe use of machinery the income of workingmen must be\nsufficient to enable them to consume the surplus.\n\u201cDuring the period while surplus goods were piling\nEntered as second-class matter Augrust 25. 1920. at the postoffice\nat Milwaukee. Wisconsin, under the Act of March 3. 1879.\n3 Sisters, Victims of\nMarket, Wade to Death\nSANTA MONICA, Calif.\u2014Three\nsisters who had been inseparable\ncompanions since the youngest was\nborn 60 years ago, and one of whom\nwas blind, waded together into the\nPacific ocean and drowned them\nselves because of stock market loss\nes and inability to pay taxes, their\nbrother told police today.\nOnly in death were the women\never separated. Bodies of two of\nthem, Miss Abba Miller, 70 years\nold, and Mrs. Ada McKeon, 80 years\nold, were washed ashore yesterday.\nSearch was started for the body of\nthe third. Miss Jessie Miller, 60\n400 Coeds Stage\nHot Class Fight\nAt Ohio Wesleyan\nDELAWARE, Ohio Scratched\nfaces, torn dresses, blacked femi\nnine eyes and campus grounds lit\ntered with lipsticks and compacts\nmarked today the battle site of 400\nfreshmen and sophomore coeds of\nOhio Wesleyan university.\nFighting started yesterday at sup\nper hour when sophomore girls\nraided Monentt hall to enforce a\nlong standing tradition that fresh\nmen coeds wear berets on the cam\npus. Freshmen launched a counter\nattack that swept the sophomores\noff the campus.\nThe battle continued in city\nstreets until police called out the\nfire department.\nCOUNTY VOTE\nOF SOCIALISTS\nPUT AT 40,000\nMADISON, Wis.\u2014Official figures\nof the Nov. 4 election show the So\ncialist votes as follows:\nFor governor, Frank B. Metcalfe,\n25,607.\nLieutenant governor, John R. Se\nverin, 35,728.\nSecretary of state, Emil Tesch,\n34.054.\nState treasurer, Alma Steuber,\n33,943.\nAttorney general, Glenn P. Turn\ner, 35,067.\nThe straight Socialist votes in\nMilwaukee county for each Social\nist candidate on the county ticket\nwas 40.000.\nThe vote cast in Milwaukee coun\nty for the two Socialist congres\nsional candidates whose districts\ncover the entire county was 45,000.\nThe vote cast for Al Benson, So\ncialist, who was elected sheriff, was\nmore than 49,000.\nWoman Injured in\nCrash at Funeral\nWAUKEGAN, HL \u2014Mrs. Jennie\nWiersma, 27 years old, Cambria,\nWis., suffered a broken neck, and\nfour others were less seriously in\njured when their automobile, con\nveying them to a funeral, skidded\non a wet pavement and crashed into\na telephone pole near here yester\nday.\nyears old, after their brother, R. D.\nMiller, Los Angeles, told officials\nthey had left him a letter indicating\nthey would commit suicide together.\n\u2018Financial worries caused by\nheavy stock market losses prompted\nthem to end their lives,\u201d said Miller.\n\u201cCoupled with this, they were\nfaced with assessments and takes\nwhich they knew they could not\nmeet.\n\u201cThey were too proud to let rela\ntives know of their difficulties be\ncause they were gentlewomen,\nreared in the old school, and their\nlives were characterized by devotion\nto each other.\u201d\nSKIDDING AUTO\nFATAL TO ONE;\nANOTHER HURT\nA man was killed and a woman\nseriously injured by a skidding ac\ncident on the Twenty-seventh st.\nviaduct last night.\nLee M. Pickell, 33 years old, 1706\nTenth st., is the victim who died\ntoday in the County Emergency\nhospital. Mrs. Jennie Ruprecht,\n507 East State st., whose husband,\nPaul, drove the skidding car, suf\nfered a possible hip fracture and\nother serious injuries.\nRuprecht was driving north on\nthe viaduct when he lost control of\nthe car. His wife was thrown from\nmachine as it smashed into\nriukelTs smith-bound car.\nMrs. Dorothy Pickell, 29 years\nold, suffered cuts and bruises.\nWalter Witijewinski, 18 years\nold, 760 South Fourteenth st., was\nrun down at South Fourteenth st.\nand Forest Home ave. last night\nand suffered head injuries. The car\nwas driven by Joseph Schmidt, 28\nyears old, 522 Sherman blvd.\nRobert Radke, 6 years old, 305\nSouth Thirty-eighth st., was hurt\nwhen struck at South Thirty-sev\nenth st. and National ave., by the\nautomobile of Harold R. Couve, 27\nyears old, 602 Sixty-third ave.\nThomas Howley, 44 years old, 316\nVine st., was slightly injured when\nthe machine driven by George Stiff,\nsame address, struck a car parked\nat Fourth and Vliet sts.\nVOTERS APPROVE\nPARTIAL VETO\nMADISON\u2014FinaI returns show\nthat on Nov. 4 the voters approved\nthe amendment to the state consti\ntution giving the governor power to\nveto parts of appropriation bills,\nwithout vetoing them in their en\ntirety, proposed by Senator Thom\nas M. Duncan of Milwaukee, by a\nmajority of 98,952.\nThe vote was 252,655 to 153,703.\nSixty-six counties voted in favor\nof the amendment, with the follow\ning five counties in opposition\u2014\nAshland, Kewaunee, Lafayette,\nRichland and Sauk.\nup huge dividends were going to stockholders. Had some\nof these extra profits been distributed to wage earners\nthe worst effects of the depression might have been\navoided. Corporations feel obligated to swell the divi\ndends of their stockholders, but when they do so at the\nexpense of their employes they bring disaster upon\nthemselves.\n\u201cThe so-called overproduction is being corrected by\ndepletion of the surplus and reduction of prices, but the\nadjustment is complicated by unemployment and lack of\nconfidence. This method is costly in the extreme, both\nto industry and labor.\n\u201cIf the fundamental relation between wages and the\noutput of industry is impressed upon the country by\nthis sad experience, there will be some hope of avoiding\neconomic hills and hollows in the future.\u201d\nIt would be difficult to state the case more clearly,\nconcisely and accurately. The cause of these \u201chard\ntimes\u201d is not \u201cworld conditions\u201d as frightened politicians\nwould like to have us believe.\nAs The Post points out, the American worker is not\ngetting a fair share of the things he produces.\nOne fact, cited by The Post, proves that beyond\ncavil: Had the worker received in 1929 the same share\nof his product that he received in 1849, 80 years ago, the\nemployer would have been forced to put $5,000,000,000\nmore in his pay envelope and there would have been no\nbusiness depression!\nHOME\nEDITION\nPRICE THREE CENTS\nTWO DIE FROM\nEXPOSURE IN\nSNOW DRIFTS\nRail, Auto, Air Traf\nfic Stalled in\nWest.\nAlthough Milwaukee has\nbeen fairly fortunate in escap\ning the approaching blasts of\nwinter, Frank IL Coleman,\nweather observer, stated that\nMilwaukee\u2019s Indian summer\nwill end today. South and\nsouthwest winds have already\nreached Milwaukee and will\ncontinue to send the mercury\ndown. The temperature at 1\na. m. today was 48 but by 10\na. m. had dropped 10 degrees.\nThe temperature may be be\nlow freezing by night.\nBULLETIN.\nBy The United Press.\nST. PAUL, Minn.\u2014The north\nwest\u2019s second blizzard and sleet\nstorm within a week swept down\nthe Red river valley op the west\nern Minnesota border today, dis\nrupting communications and iso\nlating many North and South\nDakota points. A child died in a\nstalled automobile near Steele,\nN. D., while medical aid was be\ning sought. Scores of automobiles\nwere reported stalled on North\nDakota highways.\nDENVER The blizzard which\nraged through the Rocky mountain\nregion, causing death, suffering and\nproperty loss, today held hundreds\nof travelers in its grip.\nReports from a wide area be\ntween Denver and Santa Fe, N. M.,\ngradually reached outside sections\nthrough snowdrifts as high as 20\nfeet revealing rme of the worst\nearly season storms on record.\nRail, automobile and air traffic\nwas at a standstill, while crews of\nrescuers sought to bring marooned\npassengers to safety.\nThree Santa Fe passenger trains\nwere trapped by deep drifts in\nsouthern Colorado. Rail officials\nestimated 200 people were in the\ntie-up.\n32 Inches of Snow.\nThe 36-h our blizzard caught\nscores of automobiles and let their\noccupants battling cold and expo\nsure.\nThe government weather bureau\nmeasured a 32-inch snowfall at\nTrinidad, while at Bennett unof\nficial reports estimated the driving\nwind had piled the snow 20 feet\nTurn to Page Two, Column Ona.\nMilwaukee and vicinity: Partly cloudy\nand colder tonight; tomorrow fair and\nslightly colder. Frosh to strong south\nn^st winds, shifting to west and north\nwest.\nWisconsin: Mostly cloudy and colder\ntonight, probably snow in north portion;\ntomorrow partly cloudy. Somewhat\nColder in east and north portions.\nTEMPERATURES.\n1 a. m 481 7 a. m 41\n2 a. m 461 8 a. m 39\n3 a. in 45| 9 a. m. 39\n4 a. m. 43|10 a. m 38\n5 a. m 42'11 a. m. 39\n6 a. m 41|Noon 38\nHumidity: 7 p. m., 93; 7 a. m., 79;\nnoon, 82.\nTemperature 24 hours to midnight:\nMaximum. 63; minimum, 47; mean. 65;\nnormal, 35. Midnight to 10 a. m.: Max\nimum, 48; minimum, 40; relative humid\nity, 79; wind velocity at 7 a. m., 20\nmiies; direction of wind at 7 a. m.,\nsouthwest; sunrise today, 6:51; sunset,\n4:25.","height":"29004","width":"21396"}}
